					<div class="bio">
						<h4>Eyal Weizman</h4>
												<p>Eyal Weizman is the founder and director of Forensic Architecture and Professor of Spatial and Visual Cultures at Goldsmiths, University of London, where, in 2005, he founded the Centre for Research Architecture. In 2007, with Sandi Hilal and Alessandro Petti, he established the architectural collective DAAR in Beit Sahour, Palestine. He is the author of numerous books, including <em>Hollow Land</em>, <em>The Least of all Possible Evils</em>, <em>Investigative Aesthetics</em>, <em>The Conflict Shoreline</em>, and <em>Forensic Architecture</em>. He is the recipient of the Right Livelihood Award known as the “Alternative Nobel Prize,” a Peabody Award, the European Cultural Foundation Award, and numerous other awards in human rights, investigative journalism, art, and architecture. In 2019, he was elected Life Fellow of the British Academy.</p>
